Greetings

Hello thank you for opening me up. My name is Greenie the elf I and can now tell you about my life story: I grew up in a small town in New Brunswick where nothing happened in that town. The most important industry was tuna smoking. Who even cares about tuna smoking? Me, I hate tuna. I remember one time in third grade when we were doing subtraction problems and one of the questions was about counting tuna cans. I was pretty good at math, yknow? If I hadn’t become an elf, I would have become a pure mathematician. One time my teacher even told me that I have the heart of Mother Teresa and the mind of Alan Turing. Well, she didn’t really say that, but she said some pretty similar things, and I was definitely her favourite student. Well, I was probably her favourite student. I definitely wasn’t her least favourite. I mean, there was this one kid named Jonah who tried to staple something to his ear because he thought that was how you pierced your ears. Now he’s a tuna fisherman. What a loser. Yeah, that subtraction question about tuna was so dumb. How can there be negative tuna cans? Even if you say you owe someone tuna, that doesn’t make the tuna disappear. It’s not like tuna cans just annihilate themselves when you owe someone tuna. And as for the person being owed the tuna, why would they even want that debt repaid? It’s like that joke about the accordion: “ A man parks his car in a rough part of town with two accordions on the back seat, forgetting to lock the back door. When he returns, he sees that the windshield has been shattered. Shocked, he runs over and looks in, and sure enough, his worst horror has come true: now there are three accordions.” See, that’s how I feel about tuna. No one in that town respects my opinion. It’s just tuna, tuna, tuna, smoking it, canning it, fishing it, finding a proper career that can support a family, why doesn’t anyone have any ambition? Any drive? That’s why I’m here today instead of sitting in some stinking factory smoking stinking tuna: I have ambition and drive. I have fire in my soul. You know, kid, you should try to be like me. That’s what I’m here for - motivating the youth. I held on to my ambitions despite the haters. I never let go of my passionate hatred for tuna. It brought me the fuel that I needed for the fire to burn, and it burned, and I studied hard, and I worked my bum off, staying up late by the light of the tuna-fat lamp, so that I could graduate elementary school with distinction and leave my tiny middle-of-nowhere town and go somewhere that I truly wanted to. And you know where I wanted to go? I’ll tell you. One day in elementary school, I learned about the wonders of working for Santa Claus at the North Pole and I started to work hard to achieve that. And after all those late nights, after all those years of shielding the flame of my passion from the empty wind of my community’s advice, after so long containing my rage against tuna and enduring the glossy, apathetic, slightly condescending, mindless, nihilistic, sneering, contemptuous, conniving gazes of my peers, I was accepted to Elf High School. Well, let me tell you, the hard work didn’t stop there. And let me tell you, it all paid off in the end. I graduated as the valedictorian of my high school and off I went to Elf University. Elf University was hard work and very expensive. Not that it matters though because my family is very wealthy. You know, they’re the richest tuna smokers in all the land! And they wanted me to take over their business, but me, I value passion and art over cold insensitive money, and I regret nothing. I always work very hard, I mean, I would never want to do anything to disappoint my family. (quietly) I mean, they’re paying for my room and board and everything… Hey, you know what I said about the glossy, apathetic, slightly condescending, mindless, nihilistic, sneering, contemptuous, conniving gazes of my peers? Well, I said peers, not family. My family definitely wasn’t like that. My family was definitely always supportive and I’m so thankful. Am I being recorded right now? You know, I’d like to make a statement to the camera. How does this angle look? I prefer my right side, personally. I have a tiny acne scar on my left side, you can barely see it of course because I exfoliate and moisturize every night, but it’s the principle of the thing. All right, please focus that camera on my right side. Make sure you capture my strong jawline. Ok, here we go, record. “Thank you very much for this award. Well, I would like to thank my mom and my dad for everything they’ve done for me. And they can see that all their efforts in me paid off. Here I am now, as the top toy maker in all of Santa’s factory. In fact, I win the elf of the month award every month. ‘Mom and dad, if anyone ever tells you that I thought your gazes were glossy, apathetic, slightly condescending, mindless, nihilistic, sneering, contemptuous, and conniving, I’d like to make an official statement right now denying that. And I’d like to make an official statement stating that my present state of euphoria is due entirely to my mother and father’s stately poise, compassion, and kindness, and nowhere in all the provinces and territories of Canada or all the states of America could one find such a wonderful state of affairs as existed in my wonderful childhood home next to the delightful smoked tuna factory.” Alright, you can cut the tape now. Man, that childhood home… you know, I had this view out my window of the most riveting brick wall of that factory. At night, the vibrations of those tuna smoking machines drummed into my skull and pervaded my dreams, and each night, I woke up gasping and drenched in sweat, long lines of inscrutable tuna fish parading past my mind’s eye, each one casting me a moment’s glance and turning away as though in disgust. Each night I staggered alone to the washbasin and ran my hands under the sink for hours and scrubbed them raw, attempting to wash the smell of tuna off my skin. Each night I failed to cleanse myself. Each night I returned from the bathroom, choking back screams as I hurled myself at my bed, where even the comforting blanket betrayed me with the inescapable miasma of fish and despair. Each night, I wept myself to sleep. Never again! Here, with Santa, I have found joy and peace of mind. No tuna can survive in these sub-zero temperatures. When I say sub-zero, by the way, I mean the Celsius scale. Not the Kelvin scale, ha! That would be silly. But you kids probably don’t understand what I’m saying. Haha, don’t feel bad, that wasn’t me bullying you or anything! I’ve always been sassy like this, ahahaha! Well, I know what I mean. I paid attention in science class. Really, kids these days! Although even in my day, kids lacked some spark, some inner vigour… well, most kids. Not me. I didn’t lack for anything. Thanks again, mom and dad! I guess I might mean sub-zero in the Fahrenheit scale, but I don’t really like the Fahrenheit scale. It seems a little silly. I don’t really like how that h looks next to that r. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. HR. See? You don’t like it either. No one does. It’s silly. How can anyone stand the Fahrenheit scale? You know, I don’t mean to brag or anything, but I sincerely believe that if I had a little more power, the world would be a better place. I wouldn’t let silly decisions like the spelling of Fahrenheit hold the world back. And it is, you know. Holding the world back, I mean. Rest assured, though. I’m climbing up the ranks here at the North Pole. Within my first week here, I was Santa’s right hand man! He even told me that I have the commitment of a lonely loser to his first girlfriend and that my smile has the radiance of Rudolph’s nose. Well, he didn’t actually say that second one, but he definitely thought it. It’s because I brush my teeth regularly with a special brand of toothpaste that costs 6.3 times as much as Colgate. Most people can’t afford it, and that’s why their teeth don’t shine like mine do. *Smile at kids for 10 seconds* Yep, if it wasn’t for Santa’s mild nature and social awkwardness, he would have fired Rudolph right away. Why waste resources when he has me, who can do an elf’s job and Rudolph’s job? Silly man. That’s one of the silly things that simply wouldn’t fly under my administration. That’s right, I said it: Santa ain’t omnipotent. A lot of these elves go around thinking that he’s the best thing since wrestling, and they won’t accept a word aspoken gainst him. Well, that’s a load of drivel. Me and Mrs. Claus, we know better. She knows because she’s had to live with him. I know because I have a sharp mind that always pierces through the biases and cultural influences that fog up the mind of otherwise respectable elves to see straight to the core, the seed, the kernel, the truth.

It was a chilly winter morning and I was riding the train to Santa's Factory where I work as an elf, busy preparing for Christmas. I had my work apron on and was lost in my thoughts when something caught my attention. I looked up from my work notepad and saw two of my fellow elves, a boy and a girl, sitting across from me. They were giggling and chatting quietly, and I couldn't help but overhear their conversation. It was clear that the boy was about to ask the girl out. I tried to turn my attention back to my work, but I found myself getting more and more invested in their conversation. I could see the nervousness in the boy's eyes as he fidgeted with his candy cane, trying to find the right words to say. And the girl's smile grew wider and wider as she realized what was happening. Finally, the boy took a deep breath and looked straight into the girl's eyes. "I know we've been working together for only a short while," he said, "but I really feel like we have a special connection. Would you like to go out with me sometime?" The girl's face lit up with joy and she nodded eagerly. "Yes, I would love that!" she said. I couldn't help but smile at their happiness, and I even let out a little chuckle as the boy let out a sigh of relief. They continued talking and laughing, lost in their own little world, and it was clear that they were both very happy with the outcome of their conversation. As we reached the station, I stood up to get off the train, and gave them both a nod of congratulations before heading towards the factory. It was a small moment of joy in an otherwise busy day, but it had left me feeling uplifted and happy. The elves at Santa's Factory work hard to make sure that every child gets a gift on Christmas, but it's moments like these that remind us that love and connection are just as important.

But anyways enough about Santa, let me tell you more about tuna cans. Tuna cans are a beloved and versatile food item that has been a staple in households and pantries for decades. These small, easy-to-store cans are not only convenient, but they are also packed with nutritional benefits and can be used in a wide range of recipes. In this essay, we will explore why tuna cans are great and why they should be a pantry staple for everyone. Firstly, one of the primary reasons why tuna cans are great is because they are incredibly convenient. They are small, compact, and easy to store, making them a perfect option for busy individuals or families. Additionally, they have a long shelf life, which means that they can be stored for months without the risk of spoiling. This makes them a reliable option for emergency preparedness, camping trips, or any situation where access to fresh food might be limited. Secondly, tuna cans are packed with essential nutrients that are crucial for maintaining a healthy diet. Tuna is an excellent source of protein, omega-3 fatty acids, vitamin D, and several other vitamins and minerals. These nutrients are essential for maintaining healthy bones, muscles, and overall wellbeing. Tuna is also a low-calorie food, which makes it an ideal option for those who are watching their weight. Another reason why tuna cans are great is because they are incredibly versatile. Tuna can be used in a wide range of recipes, from sandwiches and salads to casseroles and pasta dishes. Tuna can be mixed with mayonnaise, chopped vegetables, and other seasonings to create a delicious and healthy tuna salad. It can also be used as a topping for pizza, or mixed with pasta and tomato sauce for a quick and easy dinner. The possibilities are endless, making tuna cans a great addition to any pantry. Finally, tuna cans are affordable and widely available. They are an inexpensive source of protein and other essential nutrients, which makes them an ideal option for those on a tight budget. Additionally, tuna cans can be found at most grocery stores, making them easily accessible to everyone. In conclusion, tuna cans are a great addition to any pantry. They are convenient, nutritious, versatile, affordable, and widely available. Tuna cans offer a range of health benefits and can be used in a variety of recipes, making them a beloved food item for many people. Whether you are a busy parent, a student on a budget, or just someone who loves the taste of tuna, there are many reasons to keep a can or two of this delicious fish in your pantry.

Oh and let me tell you more about how great I imagine my life to be after I quit my elf job and move back to the city: I wake up every day to the sound of birds chirping outside my window, knowing that it's going to be another exciting day. I get out of bed and stretch, feeling the cool air rush over my body. After getting dressed, I head to the kitchen to make myself a cup of coffee, which always helps to kick-start my day. As I sip my coffee, I begin to plan my day. I have a lot of work to do, as I have several projects on my plate, but I am excited to tackle them. I sit down at my computer and start working, typing away at the keyboard with the rhythm of my thoughts. In between work, I take breaks to check social media and chat with my friends, which always helps to break up the monotony of the day. I am grateful for the technology that allows me to stay connected to the people I care about, even if we are far apart. When the workday is done, I like to unwind by going for a run or doing some yoga. Exercise helps me to clear my mind and get some much-needed endorphins flowing through my body. After a good workout, I make myself a healthy dinner and settle in for the night, watching a movie or reading a book. As I drift off to sleep, I am content with my life and grateful for the opportunities and experiences that have come my way. I know that there will be challenges and obstacles along the way, but I am ready to face them head-on and continue to grow and evolve as a person.
